<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-690-589 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 690 589.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  April 25 1991 v17 n9 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Industry players, workers buy piece of Unix. (ATandamp;T sells 30percent of Unix System Laboratories)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eastwood, Alison.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>ATandamp;T continues its separation from its Unix Systems Laboratories(USL) subsidiary.andP;  The telecommunications company first changedthe research unit's name in 1989 and moved it from Morristown toSummit, NJ.andP;  Now 20 percent of the shares in USL are owned by 11different computer companies around the world including OKIElectric Industry, Olivetti Systems, Novell Inc and Amdahl, inamounts of one to 4.6 percent of the shares each.andP;  Another 10percent of the stock is being reserved for purchase by USL'semployees.andP;  Industry analysts estimate the total worth of USL atabout $300 to $350 million.andP;  It appears that ATandamp;T plans to gopublic with the remainder of the company by 1994.andP;  This shouldhave the effect of improving USL's profitability and improve theOpen Software Foundation's attitude toward Unix System V bydisassociating it from ATandamp;T.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Divestment)American Telephone and Telegraph Co. Unix System Laboratories Inc.andO;(Securities).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Securities TransferDivestmentSubsidiary CompaniesStrategic Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Industry players, workers buy piece of UnixandM;Telecommunications giant ATandamp;T has formalized the split with its subsidiaryUnix System Laboratories (USL) Inc. by selling off over 30 per cent of thecompany.andM;It intends to make USL public within the next two to three years, accordingto USL spokesperson Dick Muldoon.andM;ATandamp;T, based in Morristown, N.J., has sold over 20 per cent of USL shares to11 industry players in the U.S., the Pacific Rim and Europe.andP;  These are:Amdahl, Motorola, Novell, Sun Microsystems, Fujitsu, NEC, ICL, OlivettiSystems andamp; Networks, Institute for Information Industry (Taiwan), OKI ElectricIndustry, and Toshiba.andM;A further 10 per cent will be reserved for employees.andP;  Terms of the sale werenot disclosed but Ed Borkovsky, president of Unican Marketing Services inNorth York, Ont., suggests USL could be worth between $300 and $350 million.andO;&quot;I think a guess of $10 to $20 million is probably covering the range ofinvestments made by those companies.&quot;andM;Muldoon describes the investments as &quot;significant amounts&quot; and says each ofthe 11 companies has bought between one and 4.6 per cent of USL shares.andM;The selloff marks ATandamp;T's formal disassociation from USL, a process begun overtwo years ago when it was given a separate name and relocated to Summit, N.J.andM;&quot;It's a very clear statement that ATandamp;T is giving up control of Unix (SystemV),&quot; agrees Muldoon.andP;  &quot;All of us who had to quit ATandamp;T know that.&quot;andM;In a written statement, ATandamp;T group executive Robert Kavner said ATandamp;T wishesto establish an independent USL, with the technical guidance of UnixInternational, and with the business advice of investors &quot;who will ensurethat USL is run properly and profitably.&quot;andM;The move is designed to increase industry confidence in Unix System V andexpand the Unix market, says Muldoon.andM;&quot;The bigger that market, the bigger the pool that ATandamp;T can play in with itsown business.&quot;andM;Having shared ownership of USL will remove Unix System V development from theexclusive domain of ATandamp;T, which was one of the main objections by the OpenSoftware Foundation (OSF), founded in 1988.andP;  &quot;If (the sale of USL) hadhappened before May, 1988,&quot; says Borkovsky, &quot;would there have been a reasonfor OSF to be started?&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>